Why It's Harder Than One-Time Payments
Problems That Happen:
1. Failed Payments
Customer's M-Pesa wallet is empty
Card expires
Bank declines the charge
What should happen: Retry automatically (maybe 3 times over 5 days), then notify customer
2. Changing Plans
Customer upgrades from $10/month → $50/month mid-cycle
Do you charge immediately? Prorate? Wait until next billing date?
3. Cancellations
Customer cancels on Day 15 of a 30-day cycle
Do they keep access until Day 30? Get a refund?
4. Dunning (Dealing with Failed Payments)
Send reminder emails
Update payment method prompts
Grace periods before suspending service
5. Reconciliation
Match M-Pesa payment confirmations to subscription charges
Handle duplicate payments
Track who paid, who didn't
Why Kenyan SaaS Companies Struggle With This
Most payment gateways (Flutterwave, Paystack) give you:
✅ A way to charge someone once
❌ No built-in subscription management
❌ No automatic retries
❌ No dunning emails
❌ No proration logic
So developers have to build all of this themselves — which is hard.
What a "Stripe for Subscriptions" Would Do
Core Features:
1. Create a subscription (API call)
const subscription = await payments.subscriptions.create({
  customer: "cust_123",
  plan: "premium_monthly", // KES 1000/month
  payment_method: "mpesa_254712345678"
});
2. Automatic charging
System charges customer every month automatically
Handles retries if payment fails
3. Webhooks (notifications)
subscription.payment_succeeded → Send receipt email
subscription.payment_failed → Send "update payment method" email
subscription.canceled → Disable customer's account
4. Customer portal
Let customers update payment methods
View billing history
Cancel subscription
5. Analytics dashboard
Monthly Recurring Revenue (MRR)
Churn rate
Failed payment rate
Why This Is Valuable in Kenya
Kenyan SaaS Startups Need This:
EdTech platforms (monthly access to courses)
Fintech apps (premium features subscription)
B2B SaaS (business software, monthly billing)
Content platforms (paywalled articles, monthly access)
Current Pain:
They're either:
Building this manually (expensive, buggy)
Using Flutterwave/Paystack but handling failures poorly
Avoiding subscriptions entirely (using one-time payments only)
